<section class="container mx-auto px-4 py-12">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none prose-headings:font-bold prose-a:text-primary">
      <p class="text-lg text-muted-foreground mb-8">
        Hi, I'm <strong>Moobe Pretorius Chikanda</strong>, a Computer Science student specializing in Systems Engineering at the University of Zambia.
      </p>

      <p>I'm passionate about building businesses, investing, technology, and lifelong learning. But more than anything, I'm fascinated by the process of turning ideas into something that creates real value.</p>

      <h2>Where It All Started</h2>

      <p>My interest in investing began after reading Robert Kiyosaki's <em>Cashflow Quadrant</em>. The book changed how I thought about money and introduced me to the idea that financial freedom comes from building assets instead of simply earning a salary.</p>

      <p>That curiosity eventually led me down the path of entrepreneurship.</p>

      <p>In 2023, after reading M.J. DeMarco's <em>The Millionaire Fastlane</em>, I discovered affiliate marketing and became convinced that it was a business model worth pursuing.</p>

      <p>On 15 August 2023, I launched my first affiliate marketing website, moobepc.com, hosted on Hostinger. I gave myself one year to make it profitable.</p>

      <p>It didn't happen.</p>

      <h2>Learning Through Failure</h2>

      <p>Looking back, the biggest problem wasn't effort—it was knowledge.</p>

      <p>I didn't understand keyword research, search engine optimization (SEO), content strategy, or copywriting. I thought publishing articles would be enough, but I quickly learned that creating content people actually find requires a completely different skill set.</p>

      <p>Instead of quitting, I decided to learn.</p>

      <p>I enrolled in courses, studied SEO, practiced copywriting, and spent countless hours trying to understand digital marketing. Progress was slower than I expected, but every mistake taught me something new.</p>

      <h2>A Brief Copywriting Career</h2>

      <p>In 2025, I joined Avacasa, an Indian company that helps people find holiday homes and invest in real estate, as an intern copywriter.</p>

      <p>Unfortunately, my internship didn't last. I was eventually let go after being considered unserious.</p>

      <p>While disappointing, that experience forced me to reflect on discipline, consistency, and professionalism—lessons that continue to shape how I approach my work today.</p>

      <h2>Starting Again</h2>

      <p>Rather than giving up, I kept learning.</p>

      <p>In February 2026, I launched another affiliate marketing project. Whether it succeeds or becomes another lesson remains to be seen, but I've realized that entrepreneurship isn't about avoiding failure—it's about improving after every setback.</p>

      <p>Along the way, I've also started and abandoned multiple projects, including:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>Affiliate marketing websites</li>
        <li>A YouTube channel</li>
        <li>A Facebook page</li>
        <li>Several startup ideas built using tools like Lovable, Bolt, and Replit</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Most of them didn't work.</p>

      <p>But every project made me a little better than the last.</p>

      <h2>Why I Created This Website</h2>

      <p>This website exists because I know what it's like to start with enthusiasm and very little direction.</p>

      <p>My goal is to document what I'm learning about:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>Building online businesses</li>
        <li>Affiliate marketing</li>
        <li>SEO and content strategy</li>
        <li>Copywriting</li>
        <li>Productivity tools</li>
        <li>Solopreneurship</li>
        <li>Technology</li>
        <li>Investing</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Rather than pretending to have all the answers, I prefer sharing practical insights from someone actively figuring things out. Though I will mostly write on "TOOLS FOR SOLOPRENEURS."</p>

      <h2>Beyond Business</h2>

      <p>When I'm not studying or working on projects, you'll probably find me reading.</p>

      <p>Books have been one of the biggest influences in my life, shaping how I think about money, entrepreneurship, and problem-solving. They continue to inspire the experiments and ideas that eventually become businesses—or valuable lessons.</p>

      <p>I also have a strong interest in investing and enjoy exploring how great businesses are built and how long-term wealth is created.</p>

      <h2>The Journey Continues</h2>

      <p>I don't have a story of overnight success.</p>

      <p>I have a story of trying, failing, learning, and trying again.</p>

      <p>Every failed website, abandoned project, rejected idea, and difficult lesson has strengthened my belief that persistence matters more than perfection.</p>

      <p>I'm still learning this entrepreneurship thing—one experiment at a time—and I hope that by sharing the journey honestly, others can learn from both my successes and my mistakes.</p>

      <p>If you're building something of your own, welcome. We're figuring it out together.</p>
